  <title>Linear Time-Invariant Systems</title>
<metadata xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml">
  <md:content-id>m57563</md:content-id>
  <md:title>Linear Time-Invariant Systems</md:title>
  <md:abstract/>
  <md:uuid>a7fb0c19-dcde-45c8-b2b1-321327b267a9</md:uuid>
</metadata>

<content>
    <para id="delete_me">Among the many characteristics and classifications of discrete-time systems, two of particular importance are <link url="http://cnx.org/content/m57550/latest/" window="new">linearity</link> and <link url="http://cnx.org/content/m57508/latest/" window="new">time-invariance</link>. If a system happens to exhibit <emphasis effect="italics">both</emphasis> of these qualities, then it is referred to as being an <emphasis><term>LTI </term> system</emphasis> (linear time-invariant). These systems are very significant in the study of signal processing, for reasons that will be clear when the concept of the system impulse response is considered. Using the tests for both linearity and time-invariance, determine whether or not the following systems are LTI.</para><exercise id="eip-521">
      <problem id="eip-961">
        <para id="eip-764">
Consider the systems below. Which are LTI?
</para>
        <list id="system-examples-math" list-type="bulleted">
          <item>
Identity: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] = x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
          <item>
Scaling: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] = 2\, x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
          <item>
Offset: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] = x[n]+2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
          <item>
Square signal: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] = (x[n])^2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
          <item>
Shift: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="1em"/><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>∈</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="double-struck">Z</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] = x[n+m] \quad m\in \mathbb{Z}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
          <item>
Decimate: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] = x[2n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
          <item>
Square time: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] = x[n^2]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
          <item>
Moving average (combines shift, sum, scale): <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] = \frac{1}{2}(x[n]+x[n-1])</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
          <item>
Recursive average: <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] =  x[n] + \alpha\,y[n-1]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></item>
        </list>
      </problem>
      <solution id="eip-119">
        <list id="system-examples-mathans" list-type="bulleted">
          <item>
Identity: <emphasis>LTI</emphasis></item>
          <item>
Scaling: <emphasis>LTI</emphasis></item>
          <item>
Offset: <emphasis>not LTI (time-invariant, but not linear)</emphasis></item>
          <item>
Square signal: <emphasis>not LTI (time-invariant, but not linear)</emphasis></item>
          <item>
Shift: <emphasis>LTI</emphasis></item>
          <item>
Decimate: <emphasis>not LTI (linear, but not time-invariant)</emphasis></item>
          <item>
Square time: <emphasis>not LTI (time-invariant, but not linear)</emphasis></item>
          <item>
Moving average (combines shift, sum, scale): <emphasis>LTI</emphasis></item>
          <item>
Recursive average: <emphasis>LTI</emphasis></item>
        </list>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <section id="idm263322629136">
      <title>Matrix Structure of LTI Systems (infinite-length)</title>
      <para id="idm263322628560">We recall that linear systems can be expressed through a matrix multiplication. Suppose that a system is linear; any output <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> can be expressed as the multiplication of an infinite-dimensional matrix <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi mathvariant="bold">H</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\bf H</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> with the input <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>:</para>
      <para id="idm263322623632">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mi>y</m:mi>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:mo>=</m:mo>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <m:mi mathvariant="bold">H</m:mi>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/>
              <m:mi>x</m:mi>
              <m:mspace linebreak="newline"/>
              <m:mi>y</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
              <m:mi>n</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:mo>=</m:mo>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:munder>
                <m:mo>∑</m:mo>
                <m:mi>m</m:mi>
              </m:munder>
              <m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
              <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <m:mi mathvariant="bold">H</m:mi>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:msub>
                <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
                <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                  <m:mo>,</m:mo>
                  <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                </m:mrow>
              </m:msub>
              <m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/>
              <m:mi>x</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
              <m:mi>m</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y ~=~ {\bf H} \, x\\
y[n] ~=~ \sum_m \: [{\bf H}]_{n,m} \, x[m]</m:annotation>
          </m:semantics>
        </m:math>
      </para>
      <para id="eip-967">Now if a linear system is also time-invariant, it turns out the matrix <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi mathvariant="bold">H</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\bf H</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> will have an interesting structure. To see this, we will first express the matrix multiplication in a summation notation, where <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="bold">H</m:mi></m:mrow><m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h_{n,m} ~=~ [{\bf H}]_{n,m}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> represents the row-<m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">n</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, column-<m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">m</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> entry of the matrix <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi mathvariant="bold">H</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\bf H</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>:</para>
      <para id="idm263322589776">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mi>y</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
              <m:mi>n</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:mo>=</m:mo>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <m:mi class="MJX-tex-caligraphic" mathvariant="script">H</m:mi>
              </m:mrow>
              <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">{</m:mo>
              <m:mi>x</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
              <m:mi>n</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
              <m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">}</m:mo>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:mo>=</m:mo>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:munderover>
                <m:mo>∑</m:mo>
                <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                  <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                  <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                  <m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi>
                </m:mrow>
                <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi>
                </m:mrow>
              </m:munderover>
              <m:msub>
                <m:mi>h</m:mi>
                <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                  <m:mo>,</m:mo>
                  <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                </m:mrow>
              </m:msub>
              <m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/>
              <m:mi>x</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
              <m:mi>m</m:mi>
              <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
              <m:mo>,</m:mo>
              <m:mspace width="1em"/>
              <m:mo>−</m:mo>
              <m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi>
              <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
              <m:mi>n</m:mi>
              <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
              <m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:annotation encoding="math/tex">y[n] ~=~ {\cal H}\{ x[n]\} ~=~ \sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}  h_{n,m} \, x[m], \quad -\infty \lt n \lt \infty</m:annotation>
          </m:semantics>
        </m:math>
      </para>
      <para id="idm263322565632">Supposing the system  is time-invariant, we have:
<m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi class="MJX-tex-caligraphic" mathvariant="script">H</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">{</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">}</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">{\cal H}\{ x[n-q]\} ~=~ \sum_{m=-\infty}^{\infty}  h_{n,m} \, x[m-q] ~=~ y[n-q]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para>
      <para id="idm263322542704">If we apply a simple change of variables (<m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">n' = n-q</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">m' = m-q</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>), we then have:</para>
      <para id="idm263322534608"><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi class="MJX-tex-caligraphic" mathvariant="script">H</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">{</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo fence="false" stretchy="false">}</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:msup><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:msup><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">{\cal H}\{ x[n']\} ~=~ \sum_{m'=-\infty}^{\infty}  h_{n'+q,m'+q} \, x[m'] ~=~ y[n']</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
      <para id="idm263322507840"> If we compare this final equation with the original one, we see that for an LTI system, <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:msub><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>q</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mspace width="1em"/><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∀</m:mi><m:mspace width="mediummathspace"/><m:mi>q</m:mi><m:mo>∈</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="double-struck">Z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h_{n,m} ~=~ h_{n+q,m+q} \quad \forall\: q\in\mathbb{Z}.</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para>
      <para id="eip-633">So for LTI systems, the matrix <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi mathvariant="bold">H</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\bf H</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> that defines the system's input/output relationship has a special structure:</para>
      <para id="idm263322492224">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:msub>
                <m:mi>h</m:mi>
                <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                  <m:mo>,</m:mo>
                  <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                </m:mrow>
              </m:msub>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:mo>=</m:mo>
              <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
              <m:msub>
                <m:mi>h</m:mi>
                <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                  <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                  <m:mi>q</m:mi>
                  <m:mo>,</m:mo>
                  <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                  <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                  <m:mi>q</m:mi>
                </m:mrow>
              </m:msub>
