        <para id="idm263320572544">This kind of matrix is called a <emphasis>circulant matrix</emphasis>. As with the Toeplitz matrices, all of the information in a circulant matrix is contained in a single row or column, the other rows/columns simply being (circularly) shifted versions of the original. So we can call the <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mi>N</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">N</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>-length signal <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>h</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">h[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> the <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">0</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>th column of the matrix, and express the whole matrix in terms of it:
